{{Neologism|date=March 2012}}
'''Gestaltzerfall''' (German for "shape decomposition") refers to a type of [[visual agnosia]] and is a [[Gestalt psychology|psychological]] phenomenon where delays in recognition are observed when a complex shape is stared at for a while as the shape seems to decompose into its constituting parts. With regards to [[kanji]], a study has shown that delays are most significant when the characters are of the same size. When characters to recognize are of different sizes, delays are observed only when they are of different patterns.<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=8981675 |year=1996 |last1=Ninose |first1=Y |last2=Gyoba |first2=J |title=Delays produced by prolonged viewing in the recognition of Kanji characters: Analysis of the 'Gestaltzerfall' phenomenon |volume=67 |issue=3 |pages=227–31 |journal=Shinrigaku kenkyu |doi=10.4992/jjpsy.67.227}}</ref>
The phenomenon was first described and named by C. Faust in 1947 as a symptom of the bilateral region of the [[parieto-occipital sulcus]] after a through and through bullet wound of this region. Afterwards, when the subject stared at a truck for a while the truck seemed to decompose into its motor, chassis, driver cab and the person could only focus on one of these parts until he briefly closed his eyes or looked away which reset the shape to the complete truck again.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Faust|first1=C.|title=Über Gestaltzerfall als Symptom des parieto-occipitalen Übergangsgebiets bei doppelseitiger Verletzung nach Hirnschuß|journal=Nervenarzt|date=1947|issue=18|pages=103-115}}</ref>
The characteristic of orthographic satiation as opposed to semantic satiation is that meaning remains intact. It was suggested that this is different from semantic satiation and from the stimulus familiarization effect because orthographic satiation occurs after the perceivers have access to lexical meaning. <ref>{{cite book |first=Nien-Chen |last=Lee |year=2007 |title=Perceptual Coherence of Chinese Characters: Orthographic Satiation and Disorganization |type=Master's Thesis |publisher=University of Edinburgh |url=http://www.era.lib.ed.ac.uk/bitstream/1842/1919/1/Dissertation_NC.pdf |oclc=726540010}}{{Page needed|date=March 2012}}</ref>
